are exempt from all government oversight. School officials don’t ever ask them for transcripts, test scores or proof of education of any kind: Parents have total control.&quot; &#10;The fact that this is a &quot;religious&quot; exemption may be unique to VA, but the total lack of oversight is NOT unique. There are many states that don't oversee what the homeschoolers are doing, Some don't even require you to register at all, others give no more requirement than a list of basic subjects that must be covered, and the kids in those states do just fine. Most parents use the college entrance requirements as the minimum of what must be studied, and those are easily available without the state sticking their nose into the family's homeschool. &#10;This family has some issues that the family needs to address, but it sounds like the kids will be just fine in the long run. The religious exemption in the law is not at fault here, and increasing the oversight of other families is not the answer. "/><type4:DocumentMetaData xmi:id="13" sofa="1" begin="0" end="1278" language="en" documentId="55" isLastSegment="false"/><types:WebArgumentMetadata xmi:id="24" sofa="1" begin="0" end="0" author="homeschool veteran" date="7/30/2013 4:29 AM GMT+0200" docType="artcomment" origUrl="http://www.washingtonpost.com/local/students-home-schooling-highlights-debate-over-va-religious-exemption-law/2013/07/28/ee2dbb1a-efbc-11e2-bed3-b9b6fe264871_comment.html?commentID=washingtonpost.com/ECHO/item/1375151367-694-759" topic="homeschooling" thumbsUp="0" thumbsDown="0" origId="55" notes="" title="Student’s home-schooling highlights debate over Va. religious exemption law"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="39" sofa="1" begin="0" end="474"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="43" sofa="1" begin="475" end="1029"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="47" sofa="1" begin="1030" end="1278"/><cas:View sofa="1" members="13 24 39 43 47"/></xmi:XMI>